excerpt: Immense, 18th-century palace with gilded apartments, chandeliered Hall of Mirrors & fountain show.
detail_description: The Palace of Versailles, also known as Chateau de Versailles, is an immense 18th-century palace adorned with gilded apartments and the famous Hall of Mirrors. The palace's indoor spaces are intricately linked to its gardens, all designed to glorify the monarch. Construction began in 1661 and was completed by 1682, with subsequent revisions made by French monarchs over the centuries.
name: Palace of Versailles

excerpt: Louis XIV-designed buildings built as a more human-scale counterpoint to Versailles palace.
detail_description: Grand Trianon is a stunning architectural gem designed by Louis XIV as an escape from the opulence and chaos of the Palace of Versailles. This pink marble and porphyry palace, along with its marvelous gardens, served as a retreat for the royals, including Louis XIV and his mistress Madame de Montespan. The strict guidelines set by Louis XIV were meticulously followed during construction.
name: Grand Trianon

excerpt: Restored Versailles estate of Marie Antoinette, with a neoclassical chateau & landscaped gardens.
detail_description: Petit Trianon is a restored estate in Versailles, once the retreat for various royals seeking respite from palace life. Originally built for Louis XV and his mistress, it was later gifted to Marie Antoinette by Louis XVI. The neoclassical chateau and landscaped gardens offer a glimpse into the lives of French monarchy.
name: Petit Trianon
address: Château de, Le Petit Trianon, 78000 Versailles, France

excerpt: Ornate, 17th-century gallery with arched mirrors, chandeliers, oil paintings & gilded sculptures.
detail_description: The Hall of Mirrors is a lavish 17th-century gallery located in the Chateau de Versailles, designed by Jules Hardouin-Mansart. This ornate hall features arched mirrors, chandeliers, oil paintings, and gilded sculptures, creating a grand atmosphere for royal celebrations and masked balls.
name: Hall of Mirrors

excerpt: Versailles is a commune in the department of the Yvelines, Île-de-France, known worldwide for the Château de Versailles and the gardens of Versailles, which is designated an UNESCO World Heritage Sites. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Versailles, located in the Île-de-France region, is famous for its UNESCO World Heritage Sites - the Château de Versailles and the gardens of Versailles. The area offers a rich history and stunning architecture that attracts visitors from around the world. In addition to its historical landmarks, Versailles boasts a variety of dining options featuring local products like mint from Milly-la-Forêt and saffron from Gatinais.
name: Versailles

excerpt: Huge 17th-century ornamental palace gardens, with orange trees & canals, statues & fountains.
detail_description: The Gardens of Versailles are a vast 17th-century ornamental palace garden, covering 800 hectares of land. They feature orange trees, canals, statues, and fountains. Visitors are advised to explore the secretive gardens and groves on the left and right sides for hidden spots and sculptures. The Orangery's parterre is also worth visiting in summer to see various trees spread out in the French formal garden.
name: Gardens of Versailles

excerpt: Lakeside folly commissioned by Queen Marie-Antoinette in 1783, designed to resemble a working farm.
detail_description: The Queen’s Hamlet, also known as Hameau de la Reine, is a lakeside folly built in 1783 by Queen Marie-Antoinette. It was designed to resemble a working farm and is dotted with rustic thatched cottages. The hamlet served as a refuge for the queen from the confines of court life.
name: Queen’s Hamlet

excerpt: Showcase of ornate, historic horse-drawn coaches across from the Palace of Versailles.
detail_description: The Gallery of Coaches, situated opposite the Palace of Versailles in the former royal stables, is a captivating display of opulent and historic horse-drawn coaches dating back to the 1600s. The collection features grand ceremonial Berlin Coaches used for significant events such as Napoleon's marriage and King Louis XVIII's funeral. Crafted by skilled artisans including sculptors, embroiderers, and metal workers, these ornate vehicles showcase exquisite craftsmanship.
name: Gallery of Coaches

excerpt: Landmark 18th-century church with lavish external ornamentation & an elegant stone interior.
detail_description: Versailles Cathedral, also known as the Saint Louis Cathedral, is an 18th-century Baroque structure with ornate exterior decorations and a refined stone interior. Initially serving as the parish of Saint Louis, it endured damage during the French Revolution but was later consecrated as a cathedral in 1843.
name: Versailles Cathedral

excerpt: Classical instrumental & vocal music & ballets in a refined room with rich gold decoration.
detail_description: The Opéra Royal de Versailles, also known as the Royal Opera, is a stunning and historically significant theater located within the opulent grounds of Versailles Palace. Commissioned by King Louis XV and completed in 1770, this lavish opera house served as a vibrant hub for French aristocracy, hosting classical instrumental and vocal music performances, ballets, and operas.
name: Opéra Royal de Versailles

excerpt: Patisserie, local cheeses & seasonal produce at a gourmet market with indoor & outdoor stalls.
detail_description: Notre-Dame Market, located in the heart of Versailles City Centre, is a historic and vibrant gourmet market offering a wide array of local delicacies, fresh produce, and artisanal goods. Established in the 17th century by King Louis XIII, this bustling market features both indoor and outdoor stalls where visitors can sample patisserie treats, local cheeses, seasonal fruits and vegetables, spices, cooked chickens, and fantastic street food.
name: Notre-Dame Market
address: Place du Marché Notre Dame, 78000 Versailles, France

excerpt: Landscaped vegetable gardens that once provided produce for Louis XIV & are now open to the public.
detail_description: The King's Kitchen Garden, also known as the Potager du Roi, is a historic and picturesque vegetable garden located near the Palace of Versailles in France. Commissioned by King Louis XIV in 1678, this 22-acre garden was designed by Jean-Baptiste de La Quintinie to grow a variety of fruits, vegetables, and herbs despite challenging conditions. The garden features beautiful paths, raised beds, statues, and impressive planting techniques that continue to captivate visitors today.
name: King's Kitchen Garden
address: 10 Rue du Maréchal Joffre, 78000 Versailles, France

detail_description: The Gardens of the Grand Trianon offer a delightful experience for visitors exploring the prestigious areas of the Palace. The app's audio commentaries provide insights into the open routes and lesser-known corners of the grounds, complemented by text and video bonuses. The charming cottages, meticulously landscaped gardens, and French-style flowerbeds create an enchanting atmosphere for leisurely strolls.
name: Gardens of the Grand Trianon

detail_description: Salle du Jeu de Paume, a historic 1686-built royal tennis court, is a must-see for history enthusiasts. It was here that the Third Estate representatives met separately in 1789, forming a National Assembly and taking the Tennis Court Oath, marking the beginning of the French Revolution. The site features busts, artifacts, and a large painting depicting this momentous occasion. Visitors can learn about this iconic moment in French history for free at this essential landmark.
name: Salle du Jeu de Paume
address: 1 Rue du Jeu de Paume, 78000 Versailles, France

excerpt: Municipal history museum housed in an ornate mansion built for a local businessman in 1751.
detail_description: Musée Lambinet is a municipal history museum located in an elegant mansion constructed in 1751 for Joseph-Barnabé Porchon, a contractor for Louis XV. The museum showcases over 550 items including ceramics, musical instruments, furniture, and paintings by artists like Alfred Sisley, offering insights into the history of Versailles. Originally the residence of the Lambinet family, it was bequeathed to the town as a museum.
name: Musée Lambinet
address: 54 Bd de la Reine, 78000 Versailles, France

excerpt: Lavish space presenting choreographed horse "ballets" in the Royal Stables, with tours included.
detail_description: The Versailles Academy of Equestrian Arts, located in the lavish Grande Ecurie stables completed in 1682, offers a unique experience for visitors. The academy presents choreographed horse "ballets" on Saturdays, reformed in 2003 by equestrian performer Bartabas. The show combines highly skilled equestrianism, fencing, and dance set to Bach music.
name: Versailles Academy of Equestrian Arts
address: Manège de la Grande Ecurie du Château de Versailles,, Avenue Rockefeller, 78000 Versailles, France

excerpt: Baroque & Gothic space including painted vaulted ceilings, accessible by guided tour only.
detail_description: The Royal Chapel, located within the grand Versailles Palace, is a stunning blend of Baroque and Gothic architecture. Accessible only by guided tour, this sacred space boasts painted vaulted ceilings and serves as a testament to French opulence and religious devotion. Commissioned by King Louis XIV in the 17th century, it hosted elaborate ceremonies, weddings, and baptisms for the royal family and courtiers.
name: Royal Chapel
address: Place d'Armes, 1 Pl. Léon Gambetta, 78000 Versailles, France

detail_description: Picnic Area - Lake of The Swiss Guards is a serene spot located in the southern part of the gardens of Versailles. It offers a 12-hectare lake, making it an ideal place for picnics and leisurely activities like jogging. Visitors can also enjoy a magnificent view of the orangery and the Palace of Versailles while being surrounded by peaceful and relaxing scenery.
name: Picnic Area - Lake of The Swiss Guards

detail_description: Bassin d'Apollon is one of the magnificent attractions in Versailles, France. It is located about 300 meters north of the palace and features a stunning 17th-century fountain called Bassin de Neptune with 99 gushers. The place is known for its beauty and majesty, making it a must-visit spot in Versailles.
name: Bassin d'Apollon

detail_description: Place du Marché Notre Dame is surrounded by a variety of antique shops, particularly along central streets like Rue du Bailliage and Rue des Deux Portes. Additional antique shopping can be found near the market at Hotel du Bailliage et Ancienne Geole on Rue de la Pourvoierie.
name: Place du Marché Notre Dame

detail_description: Résidence Services Seniors Les Jardins d'Arcadie Versailles is located near the stunning gardens of Versailles, offering a serene and picturesque setting. The residence provides a pleasant environment with attentive staff members like Claude and Olivia Coffy, who are known for their empathy and welcoming nature. The beautiful garden area adds to the charm of this accommodation, making it an ideal place for seniors to enjoy a comfortable and classy living space.
name: Résidence Services Seniors Les Jardins d'Arcadie Versailles

excerpt: Decorative structure in the garden at the Palace of Versailles featuring a statue under a cupola.
detail_description: The Temple of Love is a beautiful and romantic cultural landmark located at the Petit Trianon estate of Marie Antoinette. It was commissioned by the queen in 1777 from Richard Mique, the same architect who designed the English gardens for her Petit Trianon. The temple is stunning with its elegant columns surrounding the central sculpture of a love story between Cupid and Psyche.
name: Temple of Love

excerpt: Ornate gallery of statues & huge paintings tracing 15 centuries of French military exploits.
detail_description: The Galerie des Batailles at Versailles is an impressive and ornate gallery that pays homage to 15 centuries of French military history through its huge paintings and statues. The gallery, located within the Grand Palace of Versailles, features grand portraits commemorating significant events in French military exploits. With its spacious layout and well-lit ambiance, visitors can immerse themselves in the historical significance of the artworks.
name: Galerie des Batailles

excerpt: Elegant 17th-century neoclassical cathedral & historic site of French royal family events.
detail_description: Church of Our Lady is a 17th-century neoclassical cathedral located in the beautiful city of Versailles. It was built around 1630, around the same time as the Palace of Versailles, by the same architect. The church boasts exquisite paintings and sculptures, with a particularly noteworthy Chapel on the left side upon entry. Visitors describe it as peaceful and calming, often frequented by local parishioners in prayer.
name: Église Notre-Dame

detail_description: Marie Antoinette's Grotto, located within the private country village of Marie Antoinette, offers a unique glimpse into the life of the infamous queen. Visitors can explore the Petit Trianon and Trianon Palaces for a taste of pared-down elegance and witness the Queens Apartment, including the bed chamber where 19 royal children were born.
name: Marie Antoinette's Grotto

detail_description: The Tourist Office of Versailles is known for its helpful and accommodating service, especially when it comes to obtaining tickets for the palace. Visitors have praised the office for assisting with ticket availability, providing useful information on weather and train schedules, and offering multilingual support. Additionally, they can help facilitate connections between visitors through social media platforms to enhance the experience for non-French speakers. Overall, it's a valuable resource that contributes to a seamless and enjoyable visit to Versailles.
name: Tourist Office of Versailles

detail_description: This park is located in the heart of Versailles and it is perfect for visitors who want to get away from the big attractions and explore the areas enjoyed by locals and kids. There's an orangery and wonderful grounds that make it a great place to spend a day. The domain is open on specific days so be sure to check the website before visiting.
name: Madame Élisabeth's Estate

excerpt: Neo-Renaissance administrative building with regular exhibitions & tours by appointment.
detail_description: Hôtel de Ville, also known as the Paris City Hall building, is a stunning Neo-Renaissance administrative building located between the Notre-Dame Cathedral and the Centre Pompidou. It is renowned for its remarkable facade adorned with statues of famous French historical figures. The building offers regular exhibitions and tours by appointment, providing visitors with an opportunity to explore its grandeur.
name: Hôtel de Ville
Musée de la Toile de Jouy
address: 54 Rue Charles de Gaulle, 78350 Jouy-en-Josas, France

detail_description: The Equestrian Statue of Louis XIV is a renowned sculpture located in the Palace of Versailles, a UNESCO World Heritage site. The statue depicts the Sun King, Louis XIV, who reigned for an impressive 72 years as the king of France. Designed by Italian artist Gian Lorenzo Bernini and completed in 1684, it has been standing in front of Versailles since 1816.
name: Equestrian statue of Louis XIV

detail_description: Parc Balbi, located in Versailles, offers a picturesque setting for capturing the autumnal beauty of its English-style garden, river, belvedere, and expansive grotto. It's the perfect place to take a leisurely stroll and admire the vibrant colors of nature while enjoying the tranquil atmosphere.
name: Parc Balbi
address: 12 Rue du Maréchal Joffre, 78000 Versailles, France

excerpt: Park & conservation area with 2500 species of tree & plant-packed greenhouses, plus guided tours.
detail_description: Nestled adjacent to the grandeur of the Palace of Versailles, the Versailles-Chèvreloup Arboretum is a breathtaking conservation area that spans an impressive 200 hectares. Home to around 2,500 species of trees and plants, this lush haven offers visitors a chance to explore its extensive greenhouses and partake in guided tours. Nature enthusiasts will delight in discovering rare specimens among its 15,000 different plant varieties while enjoying leisurely strolls or invigorating bike rides through well-maintained paths.
name: Versailles-Chèvreloup Arboretum
address: 30 Rte de Versailles, 78150 Le Chesnay-Rocquencourt, France

excerpt: Gilded sculpture depicting the Greek god rising from the water in a chariot, completed in 1671.
detail_description: The Apollo Fountain, completed in 1671, is a stunning masterpiece located at the end of the Grand Canal in Versailles. The fountain features a gilded sculpture of Apollo, the Greek sun god, rising from the water in his chariot. This symbolically represents the king's power during the Baroque period. Surrounding the fountain are intricate sculptures and water features that add to its magnificence.
name: Apollo Fountain

excerpt: Museum telling the story of the state archives & displaying significant documents, maps & images.
detail_description: The National Archives Museum - Hôtel de Soubise is a hidden gem in the Marais, originally built for a mistress of Louis XIV. The palace's majestic courtyard and colonnade offer a grand entrance. While it was converted into the French National Archives by Napoleon, the Prince and Princess's apartments were preserved.
name: National Archives Museum - Hôtel de Soubise
address: 60 Rue des Francs Bourgeois, 75003 Paris, France

detail_description: Latona's Pool and Parterre is a stunning feature within the gardens of Versailles. It is surrounded by other notable attractions such as the Orangery, Bassin de Saturne, and Grand Canal. The fountain at Latona's Pool is adorned with golden ornaments and statues, creating a picturesque sight. Visitors can enjoy the music fountain on specific days, adding to the enchanting atmosphere. The water shows are particularly spectacular when the fountain is turned on.
name: Latona's Pool and Parterre

detail_description: Royale Factory is a prominent theater in the area, offering a variety of performances across its multiple stages such as Opera Royal, Theatre Montansier, Centre de Musique Baroque, and La Royale Factory. The venue hosts diverse shows including one-man shows, comedy acts, and stand-up performances every Thursday, Friday, and Saturday. Visitors can expect an evening filled with laughter and entertainment. The comfortable seating and welcoming bar add to the overall experience.
name: Royale Factory

excerpt: Opulent 1777 theater with 3 tiers of balconies, presenting classical concerts, opera, jazz & drama.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Versailles, the Théâtre Montansier is a stunning example of Italian-style architecture that dates back to 1777. This opulent venue, designed by Marguerite Brunet—affectionately known as La Montansier—features three tiers of balconies and has hosted illustrious guests like King Louis XVI and Queen Marie-Antoinette.
name: Théâtre Montansier

detail_description: The performing arts theater La Grande Scène du Chesnay-Rocquencourt is a stunning and well-maintained venue, offering a diverse and captivating cultural program. It is an ideal place for couples or families looking to enjoy outstanding shows and create unforgettable memories. The friendly staff, affordable rates, and overall welcoming atmosphere make it a highly recommended destination for anyone seeking entertainment and enjoyment.
name: La Grande Scène du Chesnay-Rocquencourt
address: 37 Rue Caruel de Saint-Martin, 78150 Le Chesnay-Rocquencourt, France

detail_description: The Maison Léon Blum museum is a must-visit destination that offers an engaging and emotional historical presentation. The use of videos created by renowned historians adds an unforgettable touch to the experience, while the availability of excellent books further enriches visitors' knowledge. The museum's welcoming atmosphere and kindness are greatly appreciated. Additionally, the presence of an excellent speaker makes it a truly remarkable place to explore.
name: Maison Léon Blum

excerpt: Built between 1532–1632, this Gothic church features murals, sculptures & a large pipe organ.
detail_description: Saint-Eustache Church, located in the 1st arrondissement of Paris, is a Gothic masterpiece with a rich history dating back to the 13th century. Modeled after Notre Dame, it features stunning murals, sculptures, and a grand pipe organ. The church hosts LUMINISCENCE, an immersive show that narrates its captivating history through live music, theater performances, and 360-degree video mapping.
name: Saint-Eustache Church

detail_description: The Jardins de l'ancien Hôpital royal are a beautiful garden in the heart of the city. It is peaceful and quiet, with benches perfect for relaxing. The garden has several large ponds and lovely flower beds.
name: Jardins de l'ancien Hôpital royal
address: 78 Bd de la Reine, 78000 Versailles, France

detail_description: The Statue et Place Hoche is an extensive and grand Palace, requiring a substantial amount of time to fully explore. It is advised to allocate around 6 to 7 hours for a visit in order to make the most of this historical landmark. This site offers the opportunity to enjoy a leisurely lunch and take some time out to unwind. Additionally, it provides a serene environment suitable for relaxation. The area showcases an exquisite sculpture that adds further beauty and charm to the surroundings.
name: Monument au General Hoche

detail_description: The Versailles Palais des Congrès is a beautiful exhibition and trade center located next to the Versailles Castle. The staff is professional and the wifi is good.
name: Versailles Palais des Congrès
address: 10 Rue de la Chancellerie, 78000 Versailles, France

detail_description: The Récollets Garden is a charming and diverse outdoor space, with alternating patches of sunlight and shade. It offers a tranquil atmosphere, interrupted only by the lively chirping of sparrows. The absence of proper benches leaves something to be desired, as the only seating options are uncomfortable angular installations. However, the garden boasts modern allure and features three deck chairs for relaxation. Overall, it is an appealing destination with its picturesque cherry blossom trees and attractive shops nearby.
name: Récollets Garden
address: Rue de la Chancellerie, 78000 Versailles, France

detail_description: Located in the 3rd district of Paris, near Republique and Marais, Sainte-Élisabeth of Hungary Church is a remarkable Catholic church with an exceptional state of preservation. This magnificent parish church houses two organs: an XVIII organ by Suret and a choir organ situated uniquely behind the altarpiece. The chapels and iconography within the church are truly captivating and deserve to be explored.
name: ️ Sainte-Élisabeth of Hungary Church

detail_description: The Bosquet des Dômes garden is an enchanting and picturesque haven filled with a mesmerizing array of lush vegetation and vibrant flowers. Its captivating beauty lies in the meticulously arranged plantings, which create a harmonious blend of colors and textures. The garden's design showcases an artful juxtaposition of various elements, including winding pathways, majestic trees, and charming water features.
name: Bosquet des Dômes

excerpt: Scenic golf course featuring challenging holes, a restaurant with a patio & bucolic scenery.
detail_description: Golf Saint Marc is an exquisite golf course located in a picturesque setting, boasting challenging and engaging holes. It offers a remarkable dining experience with an outdoor seating area, allowing visitors to savor their meals amidst the serene and idyllic surroundings. Positioned just outside the city, it provides a perfect opportunity for golf enthusiasts to enjoy their favorite sport in a breathtaking environment.
name: Golf Saint Marc
address: Q533+VM, Chem. du Petit Viltain À Villeras, 78350 Jouy-en-Josas, France
